[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q107 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Rebecca Harris:[bold] This is a question for all of you.  What might be seen to be the main advantages or disadvantages of having companies that are operating in the 
[normal]UK
[normal], but are not listed here?  
[normal]David [bold]Odling[bold]: Certainly, as far as offshore oil and gas is concerned, perhaps I can answer that, because we have a lot of them.  As the whole industry has matured in this country—production went over its peak in 2000 and has been declining—we have had an influx of newcomers who have brought new ideas and technologies and have taken on some of the older fields—some of the declining assets—that the big boys originally developed, and they have been teetering on the brink of whether to reinvest or sell.  Quite a lot of them have sold and moved on to other things.
[normal]For example, if you go to the west of Shetland, it is big boys’ territory; that is where they have moved to.  If you look back at the mature parts of the North
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sea, however, we have seen an enormous amount of new companies come in, bringing new capital, new technologies and, perhaps, a willingness to think two, three or four times about how to make the most of what we already have.
[normal]The number of active companies has been growing rather than decreasing, actually, and it has introduced a completely new life to this later phase of the 
[normal]North
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sea
[normal]’s existence.  It is most encouraging.  It has spawned a lot of new technology.  
[normal]Aberdeen
[normal] is probably now the world centre of sub
[normal]-
[normal]sea
[normal] 
[normal]engineering technology.  It is absolutely first
[normal] 
[normal]class
[normal],
[normal] and all of that has been built on the back of 
[normal]North Sea
[normal] developments—keeping them, and putting off the desperate day when decommissioning eventually hits you.
[normal]Robert Fenton[bold]: The advantage of this foreign investment has kept the industry alive.  Without it, we would not have any industrial mineral mines left.  In the last two years, two mines have been brought back into action thanks only to investment from 
[normal]Italy
[normal].  
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: Could I make a distinction between ownership and listing?  We should not confuse the two.  48% of capacity, certainly for mineral products, which are 80% of total extraction on the island, are in the hands of overseas companies.  That is not a bad thing; I think that is a good thing, for many of the reasons David and Bob have referred to.  It has ensured that there is continuity of capacity to supply, investment and the raising of standards.
[normal]However, we should not take that investment for granted.  If the cumulative impacts of regulation and taxation are not kept in balance, they have the option to disinvest.  That may recycle the equity into other hands, but we should never forget the long tail of independent companies who have no choice but to do business indigenously.  They are also susceptible to the same issues in terms of regulation and taxation.
[normal]There is a difference between ownership and listing.  Currently, we have very few companies listed in our sector, but there are an awful lot of people invested in the sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q108 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Rebecca Harris:[bold] Mr Jackson, is the non-energy mineral sector growing or declining in 
[normal]Britain
[normal]?  
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: It depends on demand.  Given that we have had five years of very significant decline in demand, the sector has shrunk.  Although there is some indication that things may be beginning to improve, one would expect capacity to increase.  Most of the SME companies have been very resilient throughout the recession, did put stuff away when the sun was shining and are still there.
[normal]Major companies have found it very tough.  Margins have been very much eroded and the will to remain and stay invested in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] is quite fragile.  As I have said before, it is an option for them to take their investment elsewhere.  The critical thing is demand: what is happening with demand?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q109 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Rebecca Harris:[bold] In your submission, you listed many of the current risks in the sector—whether that is the planning and regulation system or energy and climate
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]change
[normal] related issues—but I wanted you to drill down, if you will forgive me for so putting it, to what the absolutely key threats to the sector are.
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: It is really about demand.  The ability to supply that is predicated on one critical word, which I have not heard this morning.  We operate indigenously with a plan
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]led
[normal] system.  It is all about the planning and permitting.  That is the critical thing for onshore development.  We are only as good as the ability of the plan
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]led
[normal] system to provide plans through the county councils for us to be able to plan ahead.  The permitting system then kicks in, which is the regulatory side.  
[normal]T
[normal]he critical issues are about planning and permitting, and then you get to carbon and energy and all of the other issues.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q110 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Rebecca Harris:[bold] It would be something like a county
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]council’s mineral plan.
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: Exactly, yes.  That is critical; it is absolutely central to our ability to supply whatever the demand is.  
[normal]Robert Fenton[bold]: May I come back to the original question you asked Nigel, on whether the industry has performed or declined?  In my sector, it depends on what the mineral is.  There is increasing demand for potash.  We see serious exploring, because they have found a variation of potash that is exciting to the agricultural industry because of the growth records.  
[normal]We have rock salt.  We have seen bad winters and councils complaining they do not have enough de
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]icer.  Those areas are growing as best they can, while other sectors are not.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q111 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] The next question is to Nigel
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Jackson and Robert
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fenton.  If you feel that you can better answer in a written supplementary, feel free to do so.  Mr Fenton, you stated in your written evidence that the UK Government does not have minerals extraction high on its agenda
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]that 
[normal]the UK Government needs a 
[normal]UK
[normal] minerals strategy at the centre of an industrial strategy.  How would you summarise that?  What would a strategy look like?
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: This is a central piece of what we are trying to do to help throw light on these issues.  There is a general lack of understanding of the need for minerals.  This is not optional: we need minerals.  The only issue is whether they come from our island or somewhere else.  Fortunately, we are able to be relatively self-sufficient for the bulk materials, which are predominantly the construction materials: the aggregates, cement and concrete; however, there are 
[normal]metallics
[normal] and other things where we are not quite so well blessed.  Since the war, no Government has really gripped the realisation of how important mineral wealth is to the economy and to giving us the built environment, the natural environment within which we all want to live.
[normal]It is very piecemeal.  Planning is owned by DCLG; that is where the primary driver for the availability of resources sits.  The National
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Planning
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Policy
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Framework does acknowledge the central role that minerals play, which is good.  DEFRA, however, are very much concerned with the operational permitting aspects
[normal],
[normal] and the link between DEFRA and DCLG is not as strong and co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordinated as it could be; this applies to the agencies as well.  DECC are clearly very focused on energy and carbon issues and BIS are there to champion the interests of industry.  
[normal]We see a fragmented approach to this
[normal],
[normal] and it is no wonder, really, that there is no clear vision on the overall need for minerals, whether they be energy or non-energy.  I know that BIS and David’s sector have an oil and gas industrial strategy in place now.  There is a need for something for non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]energy
[normal].  This industry will attempt, and it is happy and keen to work with Government, to help develop it so that there is clarity in terms of metrics, the need for these essential minerals and the issues that bear upon their availability and constrain them.
[normal]That is the missing piece: this recognition of the need for minerals.  This is not an optional thing.  We need this stuff to fuel the economy.  It would be very helpful to Government and all stakeholders, including community groups and NGOs, if there was a jointly crafted strategy there.  Certainly through the UK
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Minerals
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Forum, where industry meets with the planners, the NGOs and representatives from key Government Departments, we have a golden opportunity to develop something that has stakeholder integrity.  
[normal]              [bold]Q112 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Would it be a fair summary to say that cross
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]departmental
[normal] issues generated by the formulation of such a strategy have so far impeded its development, basically, and there needs to be some sort of process by which Government takes ownership of it?
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: Yes.  Government
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Departments are very good at looking forward and back; they are not very good at looking sideways.  We do not have a problem with that per se.  We are trying to create a place where you can join up those forces and issues outside, but we need 
[normal]Government to take an interest and be in the room, as they currently are, certainly, at the UK
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Minerals
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Forum.
[normal]I think there is an opportunity.  As long as we have mineral development in boxes called coal, shale gas, oil and gas, 
[normal]and 
[normal]aggregates, we are not making the best and most sustainable use of this wealth, which is so important to us.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q113 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Rebecca Harris:[bold] To clarify, in this country, we do have planning imposed, to plan, monitor and provide everything for aggregates and so on.  I was not quite clear where the problem was, but it is about looking at them—
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: To be able to have any form of development, whether it be potash or coal, an operator—an investor or developer—has to submit a planning application to get approval for that use of land.  The approach that the previous Government and this Government have taken is that plan
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]led
[normal] is the way to do it.  Each county council has a duty to prepare these plans, so that there is clarity for the community and all stakeholders to see what development can take place in what location.  After 10
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]years of this, we still only have 50% plan coverage, and less than 25% in terms of the detail on the mineral
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]plan
[normal] level.
[normal]Aspirationally
[normal], this process is probably worthy, but it is actually still relatively unfit for purpose.  We are not against having a plan
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]led
[normal] system.  Let’s get some plans
[normal],
[normal] and then you will get some certainty, and that will help encourage investment.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q114 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Rebecca Harris:[bold] What you want is more years ahead of supply to be ploughed out at the beginning.
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: This is a long
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term industry.  The investments that everybody across this table 
[normal]are 
[normal]making are typically going to be in the territory of 10, 20 or 30 years, and often far longer.  This is not like housing, which is over two to three years.  
[normal]Rebecca Harris:[bold] No, it is not.  We have 15 to 2
[normal]0-
[normal]year plans for housing.
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: I understand that.  However, you can get in and out of the system pretty quickly with housing.  With mineral extraction, which is not something generally regarded as what people want to see in their backyard, these things take a lot longer.  It is measured in decades, rather than years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q115 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I think we get the point.  It was also submitted that there was “no encouragement for exploration in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] compared with the rest of the world.”  Could you explain that
[normal],
[normal] and are you saying that the 
[normal]UK
[normal] taxpayer should subsidise it?  Is it subsidised in other parts of the world?  Robert, you put in that submission.
[normal]Robert Fenton[bold]: Difficulties are put in front of companies when they want to do exploration.  In other countries, barriers are removed so that they can explore.  There is lot of exploration even in 
[normal]Ireland
[normal].  The Irish system encourages exploration; we do not encourage exploration in this country.  We put up barriers to stop us doing it.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q116 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Are the barriers what was referred to earlier, i.e. the planning system and so on?  Are there other barriers as well?
[normal]Robert Fenton[bold]: It is planning and environmental issues.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q117 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] You are not talking about taxation incentives.
[normal]Robert Fenton[bold]: It depends on how you use the term 
[normal]“
[normal]taxation
[normal]”
[normal].  The cost of putting in the planning applications is in the hundreds of thousands or millions of pounds, let alone the cost of the exploration.  
[normal]Chair:[bold] The cost of going through the process, effectively, is taxation on the company, in the broadest sense of the word.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q118 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Walker:[bold] We have had a lot of sometimes contradictory evidence around skills and the risk that a skills shortage essentially poses to the sector.  We have heard from Sirius
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Minerals that it is well known that in the extractive sector there is a national and global shortage of people with the skills required.  On the other hand, 
[normal]Intierra
[normal] have said there is a good enough skills base overall.  What is the view of the panel on that?  
[normal]Robert Fenton[bold]: It depends on what skill you are looking at.  If you are looking for mining engineers, who are the main leaders of these companies, there is a world shortage.  Over the last two decades, mining schools in this country have closed down.  There are maybe one or two now.  We have seen a slight change recently, in that Camborne has a higher proportion of mining
[normal] 
[normal]engineering students
[normal]—
[normal]at least 40.  However, mining engineers are being sought all over the world.  If we train them here, they can earn salaries many times what they can get from our operators, because there is a shortage of skilled, qualified mining engineers.  In respect of other skills, we are looking at training methods to improve people from within and train them up, but qualified engineers is the problem area.
[normal]David [bold]Odling[bold]: Certainly, the oil and gas sector has a shortage of experience in particular.  We can and do recruit many excellent youngsters, whether they are graduates or people coming in as technicians and that kind of thing.  There are all sorts of training programmes.  The area where we are short of people is those who have at least 10 and preferably 15 to 20 years’ experience, i.e. the kind of people who can be in charge of design teams and take authority for designs or who can lead a construction site and project
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]manage
[normal].  This is the area where we are short of people; it is true worldwide.  Unfortunately, that is bidding up the cost of those skilled people.  Costs are rising on that account.
[normal]Stuart [bold]Hoult[bold]: We would echo that in the coal sector.  We have an ageing work
[normal] 
[normal]force now.  Certainly, at the senior
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]management
[normal] levels we are struggling to get—and, in some cases, we are competing globally for—those skills.  We are able to recruit and train young technicians, though.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q119 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Walker:[bold] In terms of the importance of having that skills base, as a lot of you have commented, it is a very international market.  The people who have these skills can travel the world and work in other countries.  I have certainly visited mines in far
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]flung places where there are 
[normal]UK
[normal] engineers working.  What is the importance and benefit of having a 
[normal]UK
[normal] domestic industry in terms of making sure that that skills base is maintained?
[normal]David [bold]Odling[bold]: It is enormous.  It is absolutely enormous.  The only downside to it is that people who have been properly trained in this country—or any part of 
[normal]Western
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Europe
[normal], frankly—are highly desirable worldwide and, of course, they are mobile.  There are plenty of people who travel as a matter of routine.  A very good friend of mine at home is a drilling engineer.  He works in the Caspian—four weeks on, four weeks off.  This is his life.  Before that, it was 
[normal]Egypt
[normal]—four weeks on, four weeks off.  That is the nature of the business.
[normal]Nonetheless, it would be extremely difficult to measure the value of having that fundamental skills base here in this country.  None of us is in any doubt that it is highly valuable.  These are very high
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]value
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]adding
[normal] jobs.  Our rates of pay are roughly twice the national average.  
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: In a more local aspect, our sectors are providing 1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million tonnes of material every day in a normal year.  There is nothing else that moves that much material.  We need the skills and the capacity to be able to keep the wheels on the bus in the economy.  This is not high
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]value
[normal], but it is very high
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]volume
[normal].
[normal]I can understand why you are getting contradictory messages on that, and I think you need to be quite forensic about it.  Where are those skills needed?  What is the supply?  Right now, with the economy maybe transitioning into higher demand, there is a shortage of drivers to drive trucks to move the material around.  You might not think that is a highly skilled job; right now, it is an incredibly important job, with a number of people who are on the road and competing for space on the road.  You need to drill down to understand that.  I can understand why it is contradictory.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q120 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Walker:[bold] There is a lot more we could discuss in this space, as well, but do you feel that there is a healthy and active relationship between the industry, training providers and universities?  You mentioned the world
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]renowned Camborne set
[normal]-
[normal]up, but it is relatively small in the grand scheme of things.  Is there more that could be done on that front to strengthen the ties?
[normal]Nigel Jackson[bold]: Certainly, in our sector, we have a very good relationship with our training providers.  We have created our own organisation to do that, because the skill
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]sector
[normal] approach does not work for us.  It confuses and lengthens the conversation, because they have a self-interest.  In terms of our relationship with universities, it is pretty strong, but we need a bigger base, because we have cut geology and mining
[normal] 
[normal]engineering departments; therefore, the population within academe has shrunk.  Those who are left are struggling very hard to find funding to stay in business in earth
[normal] 
[normal]science departments.  This is something that also perhaps ought to be understood.
[normal]David [bold]Odling[bold]: We would certainly support that question of earth sciences, even down in schools.  We have been putting money into a school programme for 12 years now to encourage the teaching of earth sciences in schools.  However, on the academic side, we have very close links with the two universities in 
[normal]Aberdeen
[normal], 
[normal]Heriot
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]Watt
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]in 
[normal]Edinburgh
[normal], 
[normal]Cambridge
[normal], 
[normal]Manchester
[normal] and, in this city, 
[normal]Imperial
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]College
[normal], which are all well-known sources.  There are strong links, but, frankly, we are suffering from the lack of demand through the second half of the 1980s and the 1990s, when there was a surplus of energy around and people did not train as many people in those years.  In this century, things have picked up a lot and so the shortfall is evident from those who would have started their careers in that 15
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year period.
